{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":33903,"record_hash":"sha256:4fd8d0cb9a84b770e27e5a4d086a1caa1206d98770a16dafc57e3a7c85211b24","timestamp":"2026-05-11T19:31:11.767Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 649745\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2445\nOutput:\n# Agent Session Capture\n\nThis directory describes the GitButler proof of concept for capturing AI coding\nsession metadata into GitMeta, plus future ideas that are intentionally out of\nscope for the first patch.\n\nBefore using this as a coding-agent prompt, run it through the review loop in\n[Spec Iteration Process](spec-iteration-process.md). For the first actual patch,\n[First POC Implementation Contract](first-poc-implementation.md) is the source of\ntruth.\n\n## POC Shape\n\nThe first milestone should be deliberately boring and explicit:\n\n- `crates/but-agentlog` owns agent log capture behavior\n- the GitButler CLI exposes hidden, feature-gated `agentlog capture` and\n  `agentlog hook` commands\n- the first implementation captures Codex or Claude data from an explicit\n  transcript path\n- provenance and dedupe data is written to shareable-ready `gitbutler:*` GitMeta\n  keys on the `project` target\n- capture can optionally associate that project session with an explicit GitMeta\n  target\n- hooks can capture from Claude Code or Codex lifecycle payloads that include an\n  exact transcript path\n- transcript records are always captured and redacted before storage\n- no background watcher, broad machine scan, or remote exchange\n- GitMeta serialization, fetch, sync, and push integration remain future work\n\nThe data shape is intentionally pointed at two later product flows:\n\n- handoff, where a session captured on one machine can later be read from GitMeta\n  and resumed on another machine or by another agent\n- review sharing, where a branch or pull request can later reference one or more\n  project sessions for a GitButler web timeline\n\nThose flows are why the POC uses durable project sessions plus future\nrelationship keys, rather than storing transcript data directly on a branch or\ninside `meta:local:*`.\n\nA good first command shape is:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog capture \\\n  --transcript-path <path> \\\n  [--agent codex|claude] \\\n  [\n[TRUNCATED]\nook:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog capture ...\n```\n\nThe command shape and argument mapping live in `but-agentlog`. The `but` crate\nshould remain limited to feature-gating, output mode selection, and delegation.\n\nWithout the `agentlog` feature, the command is not compiled or recognized. With\nthe feature enabled, it is callable but hidden from help.\n\n## Module Ownership\n\nKeep ownership narrow:\n\n- `cli.rs`: hidden command type and CLI-to-capture mapping\n- `capture.rs`: orchestration and repository-safe source identity\n- `transcript.rs`: Codex/Claude JSONL parsing and normalized record extraction\n- `gitmeta.rs`: GitMeta target/key/value writes and transcript record storage\n- `redaction.rs`: string/value redaction only\n\nAvoid adding abstractions unless a second concrete use in the POC needs them.\n\n## Capture Pipeline\n\n```text\nCLI command\n  -> resolve repository and explicit transcript path\n  -> parse transcript snapshot\n  -> derive durable session/source keys\n  -> write GitMeta session metadata and transcript records\n  -> optionally add an explicit target association\n  -> return terse output\n```\n\nThe transcript parser should not write GitMeta. The GitMeta writer should not\nknow provider-specific transcript shapes beyond the normalized record it\nreceives.\n\n## Target And Associations\n\nThe durable session object should stay on the `project` target by default. Even\nwhen future code can identify a branch, change, commit, or pull request, those\nobjects should reference project session keys rather than own transcript data.\n\nThat keeps session handoff possible before code exists and avoids bad ownership\nguesses when one agent session contributes to multiple GitButler branches.\n\nRelationship keys look like:\n\n```text\n<branch/change/commit target>\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n```\n\n## GitMeta Writer\n\nThe writer is the only code that should open a `git_meta_lib::Session` or mutate\nGitMeta values. CLI code may parse an explicit association\n`git_meta_lib::Target` before calling the writer so target validation happens\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T19:31:11.767Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}